Let us express our gratitude for the air we breathe, the water we drink, the food we eat, and the beautiful world we call home. And let us commit to taking action to protect and regenerate our environment so that future generations can continue to enjoy its gifts.
When we are grateful, we are able to let go of negative thoughts and emotions, and focus on the good in our lives. So let us take a moment to pause and reflect on all that we have to be grateful for.
In addition to the benefits for the environment, gratitude also has a powerful impact on our own wellbeing. It has been shown to increase happiness and reduce stress, anxiety, and depression.

When we are grateful for the natural world, we are more likely to want to protect it. We may be motivated to reduce our waste, conserve resources, and support organizations that are working to preserve and restore our ecosystems.

When we are grateful, we are able to see the interconnectedness of all things and the vital role that each and every one of us plays in the health and wellbeing of our environment. Practicing gratitude can also inspire us to take action.
One of the most powerful tools we have at our disposal is gratitude. Gratitude has the ability to shift our perspective and open our hearts to the beauty and abundance that surrounds us.

Ultimately, carbon markets are a way of funneling money into mitigation. What if we had alternatives with fewer integrity issues and equivalent scale? ü§î Let me know if you have any comments or questions, or just want to talk about this wicked problem!

The experts we interviewed agreed that mitigation remains a priority and carbon trading shouldn't distract us from the #decarbonization hierarchy. Interestingly, we might also see exciting new advances in non-market-based approaches. https://t.co/TFI99e2xzr

However, this adds more uncertainty to the already questioned issue of trading carbon and offsetting emissions. We are in a world where there are multiple schemes to do so, some regulated some not, with different standards, guidelines, and integrity measures https://t.co/p4KsoXntAd

This feeds onto a global trend of more government participation or oversight of carbon. For example, this week saw the announcement of the EU's Carbon Border Adjustment Mechanism (a climate change tariff), and #COP27 saw the announcement of the Africa Carbon Market Initiative https://t.co/y9f6MsnPTX

Drivers behind these policies are that countries what to ensure the Integrity and Equity of projects, want to clarify how they could Financially benefit from carbon trading, and importantly, want to make sure they can meet their own climate targets (NDCs) first https://t.co/lpVzcGAZRA

This is huge because carbon trading had seen intense private sector activity, and related countries have immense carbon sinks, particularly with forests and REDD+ üå≥ Also, banning private trading can exacerbate the existing supply shock in the voluntary carbon market #VCM https://t.co/FvKmoT36ac
